properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, damaging hail and heavy rain. Thunderstorm activity will spread northeastwards across southeastern Saskatchewan into western Manitoba tonight. Some of these thunderstorms will likely be severe, capable of damaging hail, strong winds, and torrential rainfall. The activity will weaken later Friday morning, but another round of severe thunderstorm activity will develop later in the day, potentially impacting far southeastern Saskatchewan into southern Manitoba. ### Very large hail can damage property, break windows, dent vehicles and cause serious injury. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Humberto. The next information statement will be issued by 03:00 p.m. ADT. Gale to storm force winds have moved into the southeastern Maritime waters and will spread across the southern Grand banks today and tonight. 1. Summary of basic information at 09:00 a.m. ADT. Location: Near 41.9 North 57.6 West. About 300 kilometres southeast of Sable Island. Maximum sustained winds: 120 kilometres per hour. Present movement: Northeast at 35 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 973 millibars. 2. Public weather impacts and warnings summary. No significant effects are expected over land. a. Wind. No significant wind expected. b. Rainfall. Heavy bands of rain will approach and may reach portions of the Avalon Peninsula as Post-Tropical Storm Humberto tracks across the Grand Banks tonight and early Saturday morning. c. Surge/Waves. Swells of 2 to 3 metres will reach the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia by late this morning, and 3 to 5 metre swells will then reach southern Newfoundland tonight and early Saturday. Waves will break higher along some areas of the coastline, and dangerous rip currents are possible. 3. Marine weather impacts and warnings summary. Storm warnings are in effect for East Scotian Slope - eastern half, Laurentian Fan, Southwestern Grand Banks and Southeastern Grand Banks. Gale warnings are in effect for Sable - eastern half, East Scotian Slope - western half, Banquereau - southern half, Northeast Coast and East Coast of Newfoundland, Funk Island bank and the Northern Grand Banks. Gale to Storm Force winds are forecast over southeastern portions of the Maritimes marine district today and over marine areas south and east of Newfoundland later today and Saturday. Hurricane force gusts are expected just south of the track this morning and possibly within the stronger convection that has fired up northwest of the centre. Large waves of 7 to 10 metres will build over offshore waters today and tonight. Some of these waves could exceed 10 metres southeast of the track as the centre passes over Laurentian Fan and the southern Grand Banks. Forecaster(s): Hatt/McArthur. ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
